SIMPLE: disqualify
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: disqualify
<hw>dis*qual"i*fy</hw> <pr>(d⟦icr⟧s*kw⟦ocr⟧l"⟦icr⟧*f⟦imac⟧)</pr>,
<pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Disqualified</conjf> <pr>(d⟦icr⟧s*kw⟦ocr⟧l"⟦icr⟧*f⟦imac⟧d)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Disqualifying</conjf>.]</vmorph>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To deprive of the qualities or properties necessary for
any purpose; to render unfit; to incapacitate; -- with <xex>for</xex> or
<xex>from</xex> before the purpose, state, or act.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My common illness <qex>disqualifies</qex> me for all conversation;
I mean my deafness.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Me are not <qex>disqualified</qex> by their engagements in trade
from being received in high society.</q>
<rj><qau>Southey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To deprive of some power, right, or privilege, by
positive restriction; to disable; to debar legally; <as>as, a conviction
of perjury <ex>disqualifies</ex> a man to be a witness</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Disquantity</ent>⟦br⟧
